(6) Pencil "stroke vanishes" + large-brush "breaks rendering"  [iPad-retest]
    All three causes from the investigation (same session) implemented
    in one batch. They ship together; iPad is the only way to truly
    verify.
      • computePressure: explicit isFinite() guards on touch.force AND
        touch.maximumPossibleForce; bail to neutral 1.0 if non-finite.
        Prevents NaN from Pencil firmware glitches entering the
        pressure path.
      • touchesMoved: NaN-guard interpolation (one bad sample no
        longer taints the rest of the stroke). lastPoint /
        lastTimestamp updates moved INSIDE the spacing-check block so
        distance accumulates from the last stamped point — was the
        smoking gun for "large brush draws nothing" (at brush 200 +
        spacing 0.1 the threshold is 20 doc px, but Pencil samples
        land ~2 doc px apart, so distance reset every sample and
        never reached 20).
      • renderStroke + renderStrokePreview: clamp pressure to [0, 1]
        with NaN→1.0 fallback before passing to GPU. Preview also
        clamps base pointSize to ≤511 before passing to shader.
      • Shaders.metal brushVertexShader: final clamp on out.pointSize
        to [0, 511] — guarantees no upstream code path can lose a
        stamp to Apple's GPU point-sprite cap. Visible failure at
        extreme inputs is now "stamp capped at 511 px" instead of
        invisible.
    Files: MetalCanvasView.swift, CanvasRenderer.swift, Shaders.metal
    Risk: touches the load-bearing pressure → render path. Verify on
    iPad with brush at multiple sizes + heavy Pencil pressure. The
    511 cap is conservative — can be raised on M-series iPad if needed
    after device check.

